  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by disguising its true source. \n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**. This law establishes a comprehensive legal framework to prevent and combat money laundering activities. It requires financial institutions and specific non-financial institutions to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions to the authorities.\n\nAdditionally, China is a member of the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an international body that sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. As part of its commitment to international cooperation, China has strengthened its AML regulations and enforcement mechanisms to align with FATF recommendations.\n\nIndividuals or entities found guilty of money laundering in China can face severe penalties, including substantial fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment. The Chinese government has taken a firm stance against such illegal activities to maintain the integrity of its financial system and contribute to global efforts to combat financial crime.",
